#### Q2. When the **Airplane** class is instantiated, it displays **Aircraft = null**, not **Aircraft = C130** why?

```kotlin
abstract class Aircraft {
  init { println("Aircraft = ${getName()}") }
  abstract fun getName(): String
}
class Airplane(private val name: String) : Aircraft() {
  override fun getName(): String = name
}
```

- %OPTION% Classes are initialized in the same order they are in the file, therefore, Aircraft should appear after Airplane
- %OPTION% The code needs to pass the parameter to the base class's primary constructor. Since it does not, it receives a null
- %OPTION% Abstract function always returns null
- %OPTION% A superclass is initialized before its subclass. Therefore, name has not been set before it is rendered

#### Q8. You pass an integer to a function expecting type Any. It works without issue. Why is a primitive integer able to work with a function that expects an object?

```kotlin
fun showHashCode(obj: Any){
  println("${obj.hasCode()}")
}
fun main() {
  showHashCode(1)
}
```

- %OPTION% While the code runs, it does not produce correct results
- %OPTION% The integer is always a class
- %OPTION% The compiler runs an implicit `.toClass()` method on the integer
- %OPTION% The integer is autoboxed to a Kotlin Int class

#### Q14. You have a function simple() that is called frequently in your code. You place the inline prefix on the function. What effect does it have on the code?

```kotlin
inline fun simple(x: Int): Int{
  return x * x
}

fun main() {
  for(count in 1..1000) {
    simple(count)
  }
}
```

- %OPTION% The code will give a stack overflow error
- %OPTION% The compiler warns of insignificant performance impact
- %OPTION% The compiler warns of significant memory usage
- %OPTION% The code is significantly faster

[reference](https://discuss.kotlinlang.org/t/inlining-tiny-methods/17084)

